Good comparison — IBM GPFS (now IBM Storage Scale) is much more tunable in this area than GFS2, so the behavior is a bit different.

🧠 Short Answer

👉 GFS2 does NOT have a direct equivalent of “parallel worker thread tuning” like GPFS.
But it handles concurrency differently using:

DLM (Distributed Lock Manager)
Kernel-level workqueues
Journaling per node
🔍 How GFS2 Handles Concurrency

Instead of configurable worker threads, GFS2 uses:

1. Per-node Journals
Each node gets its own journal (-j option in mkfs.gfs2)
More journals → better parallelism

👉 This is the closest concept to GPFS parallel workers

2. DLM (Locking Layer)
Controls access to shared metadata
Handles concurrent read/write safely

👉 Concurrency depends on:

Lock granularity
Contention (hot files/directories)
3. Kernel Workqueues (Not User Tunable Easily)

GFS2 internally uses kernel threads like:

gfs2_logd
gfs2_glockd
gfs2_scand

But:

❌ No direct “increase worker threads” setting like GPFS
✔ Managed automatically by kernel
⚙️ Tunable Parameters (Closest Alternatives)

You can tune performance indirectly:

🔹 1. Number of Journals (VERY IMPORTANT)
mkfs.gfs2 -j <num>

👉 Rule:

At least = number of nodes
Better = nodes + future growth
🔹 2. Glock (Lock) Tuning

Some sysfs tunables exist:

/sys/fs/gfs2/<fsname>/glstats

And parameters like:

demote_secs
statfs_fast

But:

Advanced tuning
Usually not required unless high contention
🔹 3. Mount Options

Example:

mount -t gfs2 -o noatime,nodiratime /dev/... /mnt

Helps reduce metadata overhead

🔹 4. DLM Tuning

Cluster-wide:

Lock timeouts
Recovery tuning

But again:

No thread-count tuning like GPFS
⚖️ GPFS vs GFS2 (Key Difference)
Feature	GPFS	GFS2
Worker threads	✅ Tunable	❌ Not exposed
Parallelism control	Fine-grained	Indirect (journals + locks)
Performance tuning	Extensive	Limited
Complexity	High	Moderate
🧠 Practical Advice

If you're coming from GPFS mindset:

👉 In GFS2, focus on:

Correct journal count
Avoiding lock contention
Workload distribution (don’t hammer same file)
Proper resource design (multiple FS if needed)
🚨 When You May Hit Limits

GFS2 struggles when:

Many nodes write to same file/directory
Heavy metadata operations (create/delete storm)

👉 In such cases:

GPFS performs better
Or redesign workload (sharding)
🔚 Final Answer

👉 No direct parallel worker thread setting in GFS2
👉 Concurrency is handled via journals + DLM + kernel threads (automatic)
👉 Your main tuning lever = number of journals and workload design

