Tune GFS2 for your workload (DB / logs / shared app)

Great — tuning GFS2 really depends on what kind of workload you run. Unlike IBM Storage Scale, you don’t tune threads — you tune layout, journals, and locking behavior.

I’ll break it down into DB, logs, and shared app, with practical settings you can actually apply.

🧠 1. Database Workload (Oracle / MySQL / PostgreSQL)
🔴 Reality Check

👉 GFS2 is not ideal for heavy DB workloads (especially write-intensive)

Lock contention becomes a bottleneck
Metadata operations are slower

👉 Best practice:

Use local filesystem (XFS/ext4) per node
Or use active/passive cluster
✅ If You MUST Use GFS2 for DB
🔹 Key Tuning
1. Increase Journals
mkfs.gfs2 -j 4  # for 2-node cluster

👉 More journals = better concurrency

2. Use Mount Options
noatime,nodiratime

👉 Reduces metadata writes

3. Avoid Shared Writes to Same Files
Don’t let multiple nodes write same DB files
Use node affinity if possible
4. Tune glock demotion (advanced)
echo 1 > /sys/fs/gfs2/<fsname>/glstats

👉 Monitor contention (not direct tuning, but important)

🚨 Recommendation

👉 For DB → Prefer:

Active/passive + XFS
Not GFS2
🟢 2. Log Storage (Best Use Case 👍)

This is where GFS2 works very well

✅ Characteristics
Many writes
Mostly append operations
Low lock contention
🔹 Tuning
1. Journals
mkfs.gfs2 -j <nodes + 2>

Example:

2 nodes → -j 4
2. Mount Options
noatime,nodiratime

Optional:

logbsize=256k

👉 Improves logging throughput

3. Directory Design

👉 Avoid single directory like:

/logs/all_logs/*

Instead:

/logs/node1/*
/logs/node2/*

👉 Reduces lock contention

4. File Strategy
Append-only logs ✅
Avoid frequent rename/delete ❌
🟢 Result

👉 Excellent performance if designed properly

🔵 3. Shared Application (Web/App Servers)
✅ Typical Use
Shared binaries
Static content
Upload directories
🔹 Tuning
1. Journals
mkfs.gfs2 -j <nodes>
2. Mount Options
noatime,nodiratime
3. Workload Design
✔ Good
Read-heavy workloads
Static files
❌ Avoid
Multiple nodes writing same file
High metadata operations
4. Split Workloads

Instead of:

/app/data/*

Use:

/app/static   (read-heavy)
/app/uploads  (write-heavy)

👉 You can even use separate GFS2 filesystems

⚙️ Advanced Tuning (Common for All)
🔹 1. Increase Lock Table Efficiency

Cluster config:

pcs property set no-quorum-policy=freeze
🔹 2. DLM Tuning

In /etc/sysconfig/dlm:

DLM_CONTROLD_OPTS="-T 10"

(Adjust lock timeout carefully)

🔹 3. Monitor Performance
gfs2_tool counters /mountpoint
cat /sys/fs/gfs2/<fsname>/glstats
⚖️ Quick Recommendation Table
Workload	GFS2 Suitability	Key Advice
Database	❌ Poor	Use XFS + failover
Logs	✅ Excellent	Use multiple dirs + journals
Shared App	✅ Good	Mostly read, split workloads
🧠 Golden Rules (Very Important)
More journals = better concurrency
Avoid multiple nodes writing same file
Reduce metadata ops (noatime)
Design directory layout carefully
Let PCS manage everything (no manual mount)
🔚 Final Take

👉 GFS2 tuning is not about threads (like GPFS)
👉 It’s about:

Journals
Lock contention
Workload design

